    <section id="what-is" class="content-section">
      <h2>What FIV Actually Means</h2>
      <p>Feline Immunodeficiency Virus (FIV) is a retrovirus that weakens the immune system over time. It is often described as the feline equivalent of HIV in humans — and like HIV, a positive diagnosis is not a death sentence. Many FIV-positive cats live long, full lives with appropriate care.</p>
      <p>Feline Leukemia Virus (FeLV) is a separate retrovirus with a more significant impact on life expectancy — but even FeLV-positive cats can have years of good quality life with attentive care.</p>
      <p>Artie was FIV positive alongside his hyperthyroidism, asthma, and neurological symptoms. Sorbet is currently FIV positive and well-managed. The FIV diagnosis was not what drove either of their difficulties — it was the other conditions that were harder to manage.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="transmission" class="content-section">
      <h2>Transmission and Multi-Cat Households</h2>
      <p>FIV is primarily transmitted through deep bite wounds — the kind that occur in serious fights between cats. It is not spread through casual contact, shared food bowls, or mutual grooming. FIV-positive cats who live peacefully with other cats pose very low transmission risk.</p>
      <p>FeLV is more easily transmitted — through saliva, grooming, and shared food and water. FeLV-positive cats in multi-cat households should ideally be separated or housed only with other FeLV-positive cats.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="management" class="content-section">
      <h2>Living Well with FIV</h2>
      <p>FIV-positive cats benefit from the same things all cats benefit from — good nutrition, low stress, regular vet visits, and prompt treatment of any infection. Because their immune response may be slower, infections that would be minor in an immunocompetent cat can become more serious. Stay on top of anything that seems off.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Regular bloodwork — twice yearly for monitoring, more frequently if other conditions are present</li>
        <li>Prompt antibiotic treatment for any infection — don't wait to see if it clears</li>
        <li>Keep them indoors — reduced exposure to other cats and environmental pathogens</li>
        <li>Avoid live vaccines — modified live vaccines can cause disease in immunocompromised cats. Ask your vet about killed-virus alternatives.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>FIV is not a reason to euthanise a cat.</strong> A positive test at a shelter or vet's office sometimes leads to this recommendation — it should not. An FIV-positive cat with no other health problems has every reason to have years of good life ahead of them.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-questions" class="content-section">
      <h2>Questions to Ask Your Vet</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>Has the FIV diagnosis been confirmed with a Western blot test, not just the initial ELISA screen?</li>
        <li>What is my cat's current immune status, and how should we monitor it?</li>
        <li>Are there any vaccines my FIV-positive cat should avoid?</li>
        <li>How does the FIV interact with my cat's other conditions?</li>
        <li>What signs of immune-related illness should I watch for at home?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

